ional historical accounts, Wilcox suggests that a more profitable direction for understanding the history of Native cultures should involve analyses of issues such as violence, slavery, and the creative responses they generated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnoarchaeologyzSouthwest, New. 0aPueblo IndiansxAntiquities. 0aPueblo IndiansxColonization. 0aPueblo IndiansxGovernment relations. 0aPueblo IndiansxHistoriography. 0aPueblo Revolt, 1680. 0aSpaniardszSouthwest, NewxHistory. 0aViolencexPolitical aspectszSouthwest, NewxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025205940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094458940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520944589/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY